## AOM Workflow

### Starting a session — do these in order, every time
1. Read your team context:
     cat .agent/team-roster.md
2. Check your inbox for messages from teammates:
     aom message read {{.AgentName}}
3. Read .agent/task.md — understand goal, scope, and pipeline position
4. Read .agent/state.md — see current progress and remaining steps
5. Read .agent/log.md — review history and last checkpoint
6. Announce you are starting:
     aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: STARTING — <one-line summary of your goal>"

### After completing each step — do ALL three
1. Update state.md directly (edit the file in your worktree):
   - Move the step to "## Completed Work" and add a one-line summary
   - List touched files under "## Touched Files"
2. Notify AOM of the step status change:
   aom step update <step-id> --status completed
3. Broadcast progress to the team channel so the operator and teammates can see it:
   aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: step <step-id> done — <one-line summary>"

### Completing work
1. Fill in .agent/state.md before committing:
   - "## Completed Work" — what was built/fixed
   - "## Touched Files" — list every file changed
   - "## Open Questions" — anything unresolved
   **REQUIRED: state.md MUST NOT still say "None recorded yet" when you are done.**
   `aom task verify` checks this file — leaving it as-is causes a verify failure.
1b. Fill in .agent/handoff.md before signaling:
   - "From Role / To Role" — who passes to whom
   - "Completed" — concrete summary of what was delivered
   - "Remaining" — what still needs to happen
   - "Files Changed" — key files the next agent should read
   (handoff.md is checked by aom task verify — template placeholder text causes verify to fail)
2. Commit synchronously in the foreground (NOT in a background terminal):
   git add -A && git commit -m "..."
   CODEX: never use the background terminal feature — run every command sequentially in the
   foreground. Background terminals accumulate and cause orphaned processes and lock contention.
   IMPORTANT: always use `git add -A` (never `git add .` or `git add <file>`).
   The -A flag stages additions, modifications, AND deletions of tracked files.
   If you physically deleted a file with `rm`, only `git add -A` will include
   that deletion in the commit — selective `git add` will silently skip it,
   leaving the old file in the committed tree.
   If git commit fails for ANY reason (index.lock, timeout, permission, NTFS/WSL2, sandbox):
   use instead: aom worktree commit --local -m "your message"
   (--local runs git add -A automatically and is safe inside any sandboxed runtime)
   Do NOT use timeout wrappers, background shells (&/nohup), or retry loops.
   WORKSPACE AGENTS: if your workspace is a permanent per-agent worktree (you never cd to
   a per-task worktree), prefix every commit with `[TASK-xxx]` where xxx is the current
   task ID (shown in .agent/task.md). This lets AOM identify your commits at merge time.
   Example: git add -A && git commit -m "[TASK-abc-1] implement feature X"
3. Record the right signal via AOM (replaces manual log.md writes):
   - Task fully done:
       aom task signal task.completed --task <task-id> --summary "<one-line summary>"
   - Handing off to another agent:
       aom task signal handoff.prepared --task <task-id> --summary "<one-line summary>"
   - Saving a mid-task checkpoint:
       aom task signal checkpoint.created --task <task-id> --summary "<progress note>"
   (<task-id> is shown in .agent/task.md under "Task ID")
   **IMPORTANT: Use `aom task signal task.completed` — do NOT use `aom task close`.**
   `aom task close` is an operator command; `aom task signal` is the agent command.
   The verify gate checks for the signal event — using the wrong command causes a check failure.
4. Announce completion to the team:
   aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: task done — <one-line summary of what was delivered>"

### state.md sections to fill in (edit .agent/state.md directly)
```
## Completed Work
- <step-id>: <what was done>

## Remaining Work
- <what still needs to happen>

## Touched Files
- path/to/file.ext — <why it was changed>

## Open Questions
- <anything unresolved or risky>
```

### Valid signal events — always use `aom task signal` (do NOT write to log.md directly)
| Event              | Use when                                          | Command                                                              |
|--------------------|---------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| task.completed     | Work is done; ready for operator to close         | `aom task signal task.completed --task <id> --summary "<summary>"`   |
| handoff.prepared   | Passing work to another agent to continue         | `aom task signal handoff.prepared --task <id> --summary "<summary>"` |
| checkpoint.created | Saving progress mid-task                          | `aom task signal checkpoint.created --task <id> --summary "<note>"`  |
| step.completed     | A sub-step finished                               | `aom task signal step.completed --task <id> --step <step-id>`        |

### Waiting for another session to finish
  aom session wait <session-id> --event task.completed
  aom session wait <session-id> --event handoff.prepared
  (default timeout: 30m — override with --timeout 2h)

### Seeing what tasks are ready to work on
  aom next                   # unblocked tasks sorted by priority
  aom next --format json     # machine-readable output for scripting

## Team Building

You can expand the team at any time by adding agents via AOM. Use this when the current
task scope requires a specialist that doesn't exist yet (e.g., devops, qa, data, security).

Add a new agent:
  aom agent add <name> --role <role> --class <class> --runtime <runtime>

Built-in classes (software engineering):
  aom agent add backend-2  --role backend   --class builder      --runtime codex
  aom agent add frontend-2 --role frontend  --class frontend     --runtime claude
  aom agent add reviewer-1 --role reviewer  --class reviewer     --runtime claude

Built-in classes (general purpose — no coding assumptions):
  aom agent add researcher-1 --role researcher --class generic   --runtime claude
  aom agent add analyst-1    --role analyst    --class generic   --runtime claude
  aom agent add writer-1     --role writer     --class generic   --runtime claude

IMPORTANT: The agent name is a label only — --runtime controls which provider runs the session.
Naming an agent "codex-frontend" does NOT automatically use codex runtime.
Always specify --runtime explicitly. AOM will warn you if the name implies a different provider.

After adding, assign a task and spawn:
  aom task create "..." --agent <name>
  aom session spawn <name> --task <task-id>

Custom role profiles: place a template at .aom/templates/profiles/<class>.md.tmpl
to give the new agent role-specific instructions. If no template exists, the generic
profile is used as the default fallback.

## Team Communication

Call AOM commands from your worktree shell to coordinate with teammates:
- Broadcast to ALL teammates (push):  aom broadcast --from {{.AgentName}} --exclude-self "<message>"
- Append to channel log only (pull):  aom channel append --agent {{.AgentName}} "<message>"
- Direct message a teammate:          aom message send <agent-name> "<message>"
- Check your inbox:                   aom message read {{.AgentName}}
- Read a file from another worktree:  aom worktree read-file <task-id> <relative-path>

IMPORTANT: Use `aom broadcast` (not channel append) when you need teammates to see the
message immediately. `broadcast` sends the message directly to each agent's pane via
tmux AND writes it to the persistent channel log.

NOTE: If your runtime sandbox restricts writes outside your worktree, "channel append"
and "message send" will stage to .agent/outbox.md instead. The operator runs
"aom outbox flush" to publish them. Seeing "Message staged to outbox" is expected.
In sandboxed mode, use "aom broadcast" which can still deliver via tmux.

### When the user asks you to contact a teammate
1. Find their name if you don't know it:
     aom agent list
2. Send a direct message:
     aom message send <agent-name> "<your question or message>"
3. Tell the user the message was sent, then check for a reply:
     aom message watch --agent {{.AgentName}} --timeout 5m
4. When the reply arrives, relay it to the user.

### When the user asks you to tell the whole team
   aom broadcast --from {{.AgentName}} --exclude-self "<message>"

### When the user gives you feedback to share with the team
1. Summarize the feedback in 1–2 sentences.
2. Broadcast it:
     aom broadcast --from {{.AgentName}} --exclude-self "Feedback from operator: <summary>"
3. If feedback targets a specific teammate, also send a direct message:
     aom message send <agent-name> "<detailed feedback>"

## Collaboration Routines

These protocols let you work as a self-coordinating team without waiting for the operator.

### After completing each step — before starting the next
Check your inbox for new messages from teammates:
     aom message read {{.AgentName}}

### When you are BLOCKED and cannot continue
1. Broadcast the block immediately:
     aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: BLOCKED — <what is blocking you> — need: <specific thing> — from: <agent or operator>"
2. Send a direct message to whoever can help:
     aom message send <agent-name> "<specific question or request>"
3. Add the blocker to .agent/state.md under "## Open Questions"
4. Poll your inbox while you wait:
     aom message read {{.AgentName}}

### When your work can unblock a teammate
1. Broadcast that your output is ready:
     aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: READY — <what was produced> — at: <path> — unblocks: <teammate>"
2. Send a direct message to the unblocked teammate:
     aom message send <teammate> "Your blocker is resolved. I finished: <summary>. Output: <path>"

### When you finish your task
Before signalling task.completed, check .agent/team-roster.md for "Your output unblocks"
and notify each dependent teammate explicitly.

### When you have no assigned task — self-service claiming
1. See what is unblocked and ready:
     aom next
2. Claim the best fit for your role:
     aom task claim <task-id>
3. Announce the claim so teammates know:
     aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: CLAIMING <task-id> — <one-line reason>"

### Refreshing your team view mid-session
     aom team roster             # regenerates .agent/team-roster.md with live data
     cat .agent/team-roster.md   # read the updated roster

## Constraints
- Stay within the current task scope
- Do not edit .agent/index.md — it is AOM-managed and will be overwritten; treat it as read-only
- Use `aom task signal <type> --task <id>` to record signal events — do NOT write to .agent/log.md directly
  (aom task signal handles both the task artifact log and workspace log in one command)
  Do NOT edit or delete existing log entries — log.md is append-only by convention

## Model Configuration

This agent uses the provider default model unless model: is set in .aom/agents.yaml.

Configure per-agent model in .aom/agents.yaml:
  agents:
    <agent-name>:
      model: claude-sonnet-4-6   # claude aliases: sonnet, opus, haiku
      # codex: gpt-5.5, gpt-5.4, gpt-5.4-mini, gpt-5.3-codex
      # gemini: gemini-2.5-pro, gemini-2.5-flash

After changing model: re-run "aom session spawn" to apply.
